.TH TLOAD "1" "June 2011" "procps-ng" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
tload \- graphic representation of system load average
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B tload
[\fIoptions\fR] [\fItty\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B tload
prints a graph of tha current system load average ta tha specified
.I tty
(or tha tty of tha tload process if none is specified).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-s\fR, \fB\-\-scale\fR \fInumber\fR
Da scale option allows a vertical scale ta be specified fo' tha display (in
charactas between graph ticks); thus, a smalla value represents a larger
scale, n' vice versa.
.TP
\fB\-d\fR, \fB\-\-delay\fR \fIseconds\fR
Da delay sets tha delay between graph thugged-out shiznit in
.IR secondz .
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Display dis help text.
.TP
\fB\-V\fR, \fB\-\-version\fR
Display version shiznit n' exit.
.PP
.SH FILES
.I /proc/loadavg
load average shiznit
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.BR ps (1),
.BR top (1),
.BR uptime (1),
.BR w (1)
.SH BUGS
The
.BI "\-d" " delay"
option sets tha time argument fo' an
.BR alarm (2);
if \-d 0 is specified, tha alarm is set ta 0, which aint NEVER gonna bust the
.B SIGALRM
and update tha display.
